Bioinformatics and the central dogma of life

Biological Databases

Information from DNA, messenger RNA and protein are all found in biological databases. Biological databases can be broadly classified into:

Sequences databases -Nucleic acid and protein sequences are stored in sequence databases and structure databases store solved structures of RNA and proteins.

Structure databases - a database that is modeled around the various experimentally determined protein structures

Functional databases- Functional databases provide information on the physiological role of gene products, for example enzyme activities, mutant phenotypes, or biological pathways.

How do we get protein and gene sequences?

Sequencing - Determine the order of nucleotide bases AGTC which can be translated to provide more information about proteins

## Sequence Databases

Common sequence database include

Nucleotide databases The large databases: Genbank (US), Embl (Europe), DDBJ (Japan).

Genomic databases: Human (GDB), mouse (MGB), yeast (SGB)

Nucleotides present: AGTC (DNA)

Protein Databases

Searching Databases

Information in biological databases searched and accessed through data retrieval systems. This system scan available databases and return an output. For instance, Entrez retrieval system searches for integrates information from various databases.

Searches are carried out by specific algorithms (set of rules/instructions). One common algorithm is Basic Local Alignment Search Tool (BLAST).

Sequences are normally searched against a database by directly aligning (arranging the sequences of DNA, RNA, or protein to identify regions of similarity that may be a consequence of functional, structural, or evolutionary relationships between the sequences)

Exercise 3 Use of Blast

  1. Go to NCBI
  2. Select Blast
  3. Check the various Blast flavours and state their functions
  4. Select Protein Blast
  5. Upload the sequences we saved into the query option.
  6. Check the algorithm part. Ensure it is BlastP
  7. Run Blast
  8. Check the description, E-value, Query cover and Accession Number? The sequences belongs to?
  9. Click on the accession number
  10. What is the number BCN86353.1. How many amino acids are present in the sequence?. Are they similar to the previously identified sequence?
  11. On the right hand side of the output, click on the conserved domains. Identify the super family, individual domains, and their functions.
